## Dead ends / decisions weighed
- The prompt literally said get(timeout=self.min_batch_interval) AND 'shutdown
  must NOT block a full interval on an empty queue'. Those conflict in the
  TOCTOU race where shutdown is signalled while the thread is already blocked in
  get() on an empty queue: a plain get(timeout=min_batch_interval) would hang up
  to a full interval (same worst case as the OLD trailing sleep). Chose to cap
  the block at IDLE_POLL_INTERVAL (the prompt's own 'use a short timeout'
  remedy) so shutdown is prompt regardless of how large min_batch_interval is.
  This is why the shutdown test can use mbi=5s and still assert <1s. Considered
  and rejected: a pre-block `if stop: get_nowait` check alone (leaves the TOCTOU
  hang) and a wake-up sentinel on the queue (pollutes task_done accounting and
  the queue.empty() shutdown check).
- The cap means the idle re-check cadence for the default mbi=1.0 is 0.25s
  rather than 1.0s. This is invisible to callers: latency is wake-on-arrival
  (~ms) and it's negligible CPU; it only makes shutdown prompter. min_batch_
  interval remains the max-latency upper bound.

## Test notes (timing robustness)
- Old test_min_batch_interval asserted the REMOVED behavior (3 time-separated
  enqueues coalesced into one call thanks to the fixed sleep). It cannot pass
  under wake-on-arrival, so it was renamed to test_available_items_are_coalesced
  and now enqueues a single burst -> one batch (the surviving coalescing
  behavior; same reliance on atomic enqueue-under-lock as test_max_batch_size).
- Latency test uses mbi=5.0 + a sleep(0.1) so the thread is idle-blocked before
  enqueue (guarantees it fails on old code), then polls (<=1s) for processing
  and asserts latency < 0.5s. Generous margins vs the ~ms actual latency ->
  not flaky (5x stable).
- Shutdown test uses mbi=5.0, enqueues 3, asserts shutdown < 1.0s and the batch
  was processed. Reliably fails on old code (~5s) and passes on new (<0.25s).

## Hints & warnings
- Every item pulled from the queue must get exactly one task_done(); this is
  handled by _process_batches iterating current_batch on all paths, so keeping
  the pulled first item inside current_batch preserves it. Don't add a get()
  outside that accounting.
- `import time` is still required (used by _write_item_to_disk -> time.time()),
  even though the sleep was removed.

